ce:section.ce:para:
Fluorescence quantum yield is a key parameter in studying luminescent molecules, particularly their photophysical properties. It measures the efficiency of photon emission as fluorescence relative to photon absorption. In this study, the fluorescence quantum yield of compound 1a in DMSO was ΦF = 0.211, while compound 2a had a significantly lower yield of ΦF = 0.013 (Table 1
                           ). Compared to the standard unsubstituted ZnPc (ΦF = 0.20 in DMSO), compound 1a exhibited a similar fluorescence quantum yield, whereas compound 2a showed a considerable reduction. This lower value suggests that the heavy In central atom enhances intersystem crossing (ISC), reducing fluorescence efficiency. The emission, excitation, and absorption spectra of the compounds are shown in Figs. 7 and 8

                           .

In sono-photochemical studies, the solution was first exposed to ultrasound at 35 kHz for 5-second intervals, followed by light exposure at an intensity of 7.05 × 1015 photons s-1 cm-2, for 5-second intervals, to record changes in absorption. The resulting singlet oxygen quantum yields (Φ∆ SPDT) were 0.92 for complex 1a, 0.96 for complex 2a, 0.74 for 1@cys-GQDs and 0.84 for 2@cys-GQDs. A comparison of photochemical and sono-photochemical quantum yields shows a significant increase in ΦΔ
                            values for all complexes (Figs. 9–12



                           ), highlighting the enhanced efficacy of the combined treatment in singlet oxygen production. Indium-containing complexes continued to generate more singlet oxygen than zinc phthalocyanines, confirming the impact of the heavy atom effect. However, in sono-photochemical studies, quantum dot derivatives produced lower yields than complexes 1a and 2a.

In photodynamic therapy, photosensitizers must remain stable under the irradiation source during the process of singlet oxygen generation. For this purpose, in this study, absorption changes within the Q band range (600–700 nm) were monitored to record UV–Vis spectra with 10 min intervals of photoirradiation. The photodegradation quantum yields were determined as Φd = 4.2 × 10–5 for compound 1 and Φd = 32 × 10–5 for compound 2 (Figs. 13
                           , 14
                           ). According to literature, stable complexes typically exhibit photodegradation capabilities ranging between 10–6 and 10–3 [61,62]. The results from this study suggest that the synthesized complexes demonstrate moderate stability under light exposure, indicating their possible suitability for photodynamic therapy applications. This stability ensures that the compounds do not undergo significant decomposition upon light exposure, reinforcing their potential as effective sensitizers.
